From John De Armond Subject Re Ammo in a fire was Re WACO burning Rick Bressler writes Small arms rounds set off outside of a firearm pose little risk except possibly eye injuries and minor Large concentrations of ammo or 'magazines' not the type you insert into your semi auto probably pose a larger risk but mostly from heat and This is also covered in the above No more risk than smaller stashes unless the stash is somehow confined so the heat from early ignitions could somehow bulk heat the Two years ago this month my house and office In my office was my reloading On the top shelf next to the wooden ceiling was about lbs of smokeless powder lbs of black powder several thousand primers and a couple thousand loaded rounds primarily in and The fire was extinguished before the area containing the reloading supplies were fully There was about of char on the joists subsequently removed by Lots of heat in other None of the powder kegs One can of pistol powder No explosion as the can opened at the seam as it was designed to The black powder cans were charred and got so hot the plastic lids completely melted and ran down The smokless powder was contained mostly in lb cardboard or metal The kegs were charred badly enough that the paper labels burned completely off and in the case of the metal cans the plastic lids melted completely Many of the rounds cooked They were in close proximity to wood on all sides so the effects were easy to In most cases with the rifle ammo the cartridge cases ruptured in the Many bullets were found still in the Small shards of brass were lightly stuck into the Lightly enough that brushing them with a fingertip would usually dislodge Primers generally popped out of the primer The rounds that cooked off left empty cases and bullets laying No dents were observed above the storage area indicating the bullets left the cases slowly enough not to be a Ordinary small arms ammo is NOT a hazard when cooking off regardless of what the FBI John John De Armond